\par <I> <h> }{<#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Conclusions and Policy Implications </h>
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 The foregoing review, based on the data and research literature on the various levels and subsectors of education in the subregion in the course of the last two decades, leads to a few conclusions - general and specific.
\par <h> }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 General </h>
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 In genera
l, the overall performance in the subregion as a whole has not been very satisfactory, with a preponderance of low performance ratings as compared to positive or average ratings. <#/>In particular, performance has been less satisfactory in four of the six
 areas examined, namely in primary education, science education, vocational-technical training and medium of instruction. <#/>It has been generally satisfactory in higher education and average in secondary education.
\par <#/>These qualitative ratings of 'satisfactory' (or higher performance), 'average' and 'less satisfactory' (or lower performance) relate strictly to the extent to which }{\fs24\ul\lang2057 practice}{\fs24\lang2057  has kept pace or consistency with }{
\fs24\ul\lang2057 policy objectives}{\fs24\lang2057  and/or the extent to which policy shifts over time have kept pace 
or consistency with the development aspirations as expressed in various popular or else representative fora of expertise. <#/>The ratings thus relate more to qualitative improvements and less to mere quantitative statistics, as in the case of expansionary
 enrolments without corresponding qualitative changes or backups.
\par <#/>Table 8.1, standing on the strength of the above mentioned qualitative definition, summarizes the overall evaluation as emerges from the review of the six areas representing the levels and subsectors under study.
\par <#/>Performance by individual countries with respect to the totality of the areas surveyed varies, as demonstrated in Table 8.2, with Botswana seeming to have done the best of all the sample countries overall, with higher performa
nce ratings in four of the six areas, an average rating in one area and a lower performance rating in one area. <#/>Botswana is followed by Lesotho (with 3v, 1vx, 2x), Swaziland (with 3v, 3x) and Kenya (with 2v, 2vx, 2x), while the other four countries, n
amely Zambia (1v, 2vx, 3x), Tanzania (1v, 2vx, 3x), Uganda (1v, 3x, 2?) and Malawi (1v, 1vx, 4x), have tended to gravitate towards lower performance.
\par [...]
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 If the qualitative judgements were to be given numeric values, both the analyses of the separate 
levels and subsectors for the whole subregional sample and the analyses of individual <-/cuntries> by their six areas of review would yield a generally similar rating pattern, with a statistically indicative (though in no way politically judgemental) rank
ing order. <#/>Table 8.3 attempts such a numeric translation of the qualitative statements, with higher performance (or satisfactory) awarded 10, average 5 and lower performance (or less satisfactory) awarded 1.
\par <#/>Of the subregion's six areas of review, h
igher education scores the highest total of numeric points (80), with a corresponding highest average numeric score (10). <#/>Higher education is followed in performance by secondary education (7.14, some points above average), primary education (4.88, ju
st below average), vocational-technical training (3.75, well below average), science education (2.14, far below average) and language medium of instruction (1.5, very far below average).
\par <#/>With respect to performance by individual members of the sample gr
ouping, according to Table 8.3, Botswana comes out with the highest average score (7.67, well above average), followed by Lesotho (6.17, some way above average). <#/>Swaziland and Kenya are just above average, with 5.50 and 5.33, respectively. <#/>The oth
e
r four countries, Tanzania (3.83), Zambia (3.83), Uganda (3.25) and Malawi (3.17), all have their scores well below average. <#/>The general interpretation is that while these latter four countries have lagged behind the others in overall educational deve
lopment, they have, at least hypothetically, performed below average.
\par <#/>The simple statistical aid used to arrive at some more detailed synthesis, and at some ranking order, does at the same time point to a cautionary note. <#/>It is apparent that even th
e first and the second countries on the ranking scale fall short of the best possible level of performance in the totality of the different areas of education examined. <#/>Their positions in the ranking scheme cannot, therefore, be cause for complacency 
a
nd reduced national effort. <#/>Notwithstanding the caution sounded, however, the relatively widely differentiated numeric scores and ranking of these and other countries under study may help further in the discussion of interlinkage of factors and proces
ses in the wider national economy.
\par <#/>Curiously, but perhaps not altogether just coincidentally, the general order of the ratings and ranking (as indicated in Table 8.3) appears to have roughly parallel resemblance with the general order of ratings elsewhe
re in some vital sectors of the economy. <#/>A specific example is the rate of production (ref Table 1.1), which is itself considered a proxy for productivity at least insofar as a heightened production of goods and services may be a measure of workers' k
n
owledge, skill and performance. <#/>While, for all the countries of the sample grouping except Lesotho, the rate of production (GDP) has declined over the past two decades, it has unequivocally been the highest in Botswana. <#/>On average, for the whole t
wenty year period of 1965-84, Botswana has been followed in the rate of production by Kenya and Swaziland, while, for the latter decade of 1973-83/84 it is followed by Lesotho, Kenya and Swaziland.
\par <#/>The same "top-ranging" countries happen to have a disti
nctively higher level of income (cf. GNP per capita for Botswana - US$840, Swaziland - $790, Lesotho - $530, Kenya - $316, as contrasted from that of Malawi - $180, Uganda - $230, Tanzania - $250 and Zambia - $300) and a higher average annual per capita i
ncome growth over the whole two-decade period (cf. Botswana: 8.8%, Lesotho: 5.9%, Swaziland: 4.0% and Kenya: 1.9%, as contrasted, for instance, from Uganda's -2.9%, Zambia's -1.7% and Tanzania's -0.3%).
\par <#/>Again, three of the four "top-ranging" countries h
appen to record the highest known proportion of their state expenditure on education (Kenya: 20%, Botswana: 18% and Lesotho: 17%), as contrasted from Tanzania's extreme case of a mere 7%, or about 13 per cent in Uganda and in Malawi.
\par <#/>It does seem that 
even if allowance were made for several intervening factors or variables or the rate of production, such as the amount of initial resources and capital base, ecology, health care or international trade relations, still the final product is to some extent 
a
 reflection of the efficiency of a country's education system, the intensity and manner of its human resource development and deployment strategies and the internal and external efficiency of its skill training programmes, including vocational-technical t
r
aining and science education. <#/>These education-related factors are, in the short or long run, bound to influence the rate of economic-material production, which, in turn, would have a direct influence not only on the rate of individual and national pro
d
uctivity but also on the tempo of income generation as well as on the level of income itself. <#/>As things are at the moment, only three countries (Botswana, Lesotho and Swaziland) seem to have a consistently high score on all the three levels of formal 
education; only two countries (Botswana and Kenya) have a high score on vocational-technical training; and only two countries (Botswana and Zambia) reach an <-/averatge> score in science education.
\par <#/>The rest of this chapter summarizes the conclusions and the policy implications with respect to each of the six areas of the review.
\par <h> }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Primary Education </h>
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Development in primary education in eastern and southern Africa has been reflected in an <-/undisputably> quantitative expansion in pupil enro
lment rates. <#/>Expansion in any other terms backup educational equipment, textbooks, supplementary reading material for pupils, and teacher supply - has been minimal in spite of some innovative but largely defective stop-gap measures. <#/>In some cases 
the expansion has in fact been negative if only in proportion to the explosive enrolment rates in the wake of the universal primary education (UPE) drive characterizing the whole decade of the 1970s/80s.
\par <#/>The whole post-independence period under review is thus seen to have been a period of expansion much more in quantitative terms and much less in qualitative terms. <#/>Problems of quality are discerned in the internal inefficiency reported in almost a
ll countries under review: <-/inoptimally> high pupil-teacher ratios, hasty and inadequate teacher training programmes resulting in poor teacher classroom performance, and crowded curricula made worse by dire shortages of teaching-learning materials.

\par <#/>At
 the end of the primary education cycle, according to most of the reviewed literature, most children show a conspicuous level of underachievement bordering, in some cases, on wholesale illiteracy. <#/>Yet, their hopes and aspirations (just as their own pa
r
ents') are further frustrated by the little chance they have of either advancing to secondary level education, or proceeding to some post-primary vocational training, or simply being absorbed into the social economy as gainfully employed individuals in th
e community. <#/>These, too, are sad issues related to the external efficiency of an education system.
\par <#/>Of the eight countries of the study sample, Malawi and Tanzania seem to have experienced problems of primary education the most, followed by Zambia and Kenya.
\par <#/>Implications for future policy towards primary education are fairly clear.
\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <h> }{<#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 1. Quality versus Quantity </h>
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 It is essential now for governments to de-emphasize and decelerate quantitative expansion as seen in inflationary pupil enr
olment and, instead, to stress and pursue the quality side of primary education. <#/>Availability and efficient distribution of school equipment, textbooks, teaching-learning aids and supplementary readers should now be the objective; for, indeed, these h
ave much more to say for a person's fuller learning than mere attendance in a classroom that had no chalk, books, aids or even desks for the day's lesson.
\par <#/>While the country's primary school system should remain open to receive beginners, it should at th
e same time remain an open option for the parent to apply for the admission of the child. <#/>Parents have a propensity to send children to school - even to pay for their education - when they have trust in the school. <#/>Public trust and confidence in t
he schools will depend on how equipped they are to impart permanent <-_learnings><+_learning> in the children.
\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <h> }{<#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 2. Streamlining and Rationalizing the Primary School Curriculum </h>
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 There should be a reversal of the current tendency to overload t
he curriculum with so many subjects which, in the end, reduce the time period devoted or devotable to any specific subject while also reducing the interconnectedness of the subject matter and the transferability of basic concepts. <#/>This point argues fo
r
 a core curriculum, based on a careful determination and selection of "central" subjects and subject areas that are accepted as basic or <-/foundational> for the learning and perceptive scope consonant with the age levels circumscribed by the limited prim
ary education cycle.
\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <h> }{<#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 3. Reforming and Strengthening the Teacher Training Programme </h>
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Teacher training programmes directed at producing primary school teachers deserve serious attention to matters ranging from selection of candidates, to acad
emic abilities in the subjects for which they are to be trained to teach, to duration of training.
\par <#/>With particular regard to candidates, selection of "failed" primary or secondary school leavers for the teaching profession as has been the case in some 
countries, has undermined and would continue to undermine not only the efficiency but also the status and respectability of the teaching profession itself. <#/>And, in any case, training a primary school leaver for teaching a primary school child is itsel
f
 of questionable merit, allowable only in special and extenuating circumstances. <#/>Similarly, the stop-gap measure - elsewhere defended as an innovative shortcut of "distance teacher training" has revealed not only inherent organizational and profession
al weaknesses but also larger unintended costs of retraining and reorientation.
\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <h> }{<#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 4. Increased Public Financing of Primary Education </h>
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 The government ought to step up the current level of financing of primary education in order to meet the req
uired material and pedagogical standards of basic education. <#/>This view is in recognition of the logic that primary education is a foundation level beyond which - at least for the foreseeable future in many countries in the subregion and in the region 
a
s a whole - a still greater proportion of the population will not have a formal opportunity for advanced learning. <#/>It is imperative therefore that the education offered at this basic level must receive all the physical, material, intellectual and prof
essional supports possible for a permanent functionality of the future citizens.
\par <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>Indeed, a stepped-up level of public financing should be possible and easier as governmental financial commitment in higher, especially university, education could be stepp
ed down in invitation to private sector participation in cost-sharing by parents, students and non\-governmental institutions (see Higher Education).
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Recently developed countries like Japan and Norway have succeeded in this area largely because of an early and consistent decision to invest heavily in quality education at elementary (primary) level. }{\v <#/>}{
\v\fs24\lang2057 The argument has been that any gaps and deficiencies at this early stage would undermine learning and mastery at all the subsequent levels. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 At the sam
e time, higher, especially university education and especially in Japan, is paid for not directly by the state but by parents (through cash fees payment), students (through loan systems with government and/or financial institutions) and industry, companie
s and firms (through charity, trust funds and/or contract research-and-development projects).
\par <h> }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Secondary Education </h>
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 With an overriding concern for indigenous high-level manpower development, secondary education has enjoyed accelerated expans
ion both in pupil intake and in the material provision of school structures and equipment, although, with the onset of the economic clout associated with the oil crisis of the 1970s, government efforts alone have been limited.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 With this limitation acknowledged in basic socio-economic principles and/or anticipated from the world economic trends, some states in the subregion did encourage partnership with non\-
governmental institutions, from an early start, for a boosted secondary education provision. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
Specifically, Lesotho, Kenya and Botswana are known to have positively and fully exploited the partnership with private trusts, communities and religious missions, all which have responded with active investment in the education sector. }{\v <#/>}{
\v\fs24\lang2057 The size of high-level and medium-level manpower to be seen across the economy that were produced by concerted public and private efforts in these countries is quite considerable.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Such faster effects of combined effort have not been realized as much in Tanzania and Z
ambia, in both of which countries, particularly in the former, ideological battles and contradictions have much in explaining the belated appeal to and the belated and frequently wavering response by such would-be partners in progress.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Not much public and research information was available to allow adequate assessment of the position of Malawi, Swaziland and Uganda on this matter.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 As regards the quality backups to quantitative expansion, some countries, especially Tanzania and Kenya, sought to refor
m the curriculum in such a way as to diversify and vocationalize it enough to produce manpower of a skilled job-entry-level status. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
For reasons detailed in the review, this strategy in curriculum innovation seems to have been an effort based on a wrong
 theoretical premise, leading as it has done to such undesirable effects as an overladen curriculum, unproven cost-effectiveness of biases, and manpower wastage.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Among the rest of the sample countries, Swaziland was saved from the trappings by formally tarrying }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>lexeme}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
 towards the "curriculum diversification and vocationalization" decision, which she has not taken to date. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
And as for Botswana, Lesotho and Zambia, the reservation with which they have had to reform and adapt their secondary school curricula has spared them from the otherwise full-scale effects experienced by the pioneering two states.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Two major themes emerge from the review of the developments in secondary education, which deserve comment in underlining implications for future policy.
\par }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> }{\v <#/>}{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 1. Public-Private Partnership in Secondary Education Provision </h>
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Evidently, those countries that maintained a consistent and encouraging relationship with non\-governmental institutions - religious bodies, private firms and trusts, co
mmunity organizations - have had a demonstrable advantage in boosting the quantity, spread and quality of secondary education. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
The burden on the shoulders of the state has been considerably lesser in such countries than in those in which, for ideological and other reasons, the relationship has suffered vicissitudes.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Inasfar as there is still and will continue to be a great need not only for a functionally educated manpower but also for the sheer expansion of the knowledge base and perceptive levels 
of a nation's citizenry, partnership and mutual assistance of governmental and non-governmental agencies must be upheld and invigorated. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
For the sake of uniformity of standards and quality control, the government can retain the right of inspection and supervision of private schools as has always been for public schools. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
And for the sake of equity, it could concentrate priority assistance on areas and districts that seem to lag behind in the general trend of the education enterprise.
\par }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> }{\v <#/>}{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 2. Rationalizing the Curriculum </h>
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 In view of the evidence from the review of the experiences with curriculum d
iversification and vocationalization in Tanzania and Kenya within the subregion, and in Colombia in South America, the experiment is no longer worthy of further pursuit. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
A regular secondary school curriculum, enriched by the regular fully fledged disciplines and pruned of extracurricular digressions into non-job-entry reorientations seem to be the most appropriate guide to the full maturity of the youths. }{\v <#/>}{
\v\fs24\lang2057 For, not until then would they be intellectually ready either to take on meaningful occupational training for middle-level job entry or to assume advanced studies with confidence and unattenuated abilities.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The serious job of parallel vocational training - as opposed to half-hearted vocational familiarization - should better be left to specific fulltime vocational training institutions (see Vocational-Technical Training).
\par <h> }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Higher Education </h>
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The review of literature on higher education suggests that the countries under study 
have made considerable progress in the enrolment, training and deployment of local manpower even though, it is to be acknowledged, the rates of student intake and graduate output are based on the small proportions of candidates reaching and passing at the
 secondary school level.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
A proliferation of middle-level tertiary institutions is observed in every country, which suggests the keen interest governments have had in developing manpower of intermediate skills for the various expanded sectors of post-independence economy. }{\v 
<#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
At the same time, however, this has in some countries been at the expense of more insightful planning and coordination that could have avoided duplication of functions in cases of similar training institutions set up or funded by dif
ferent sponsors, internal or external.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 At the highest level, evidence from the literature does testify to efforts having been made in the different countries in the direction of expanding and diversifying university programmes as well as in the univers
ities' positive response to their nations' development needs through teaching, research and public consultancy.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 It is in this seemingly "grey area", however, that the literature also points to one problem universities have suffered in the wake of a con
flict between their search for and speaking about the "truth', on the one hand, and the political demands and administrative directives of the state on the other. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
Along with this historical problem of conflict attendant on the crisis of a double-faced 
identity has been the now familiar problem of the decline in the financing of universities and the consequential decline not only in the tempo of research work but also in the extent of intellectual commitment to scholarship among their staff and students
.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 In general, all the eight countries of the study sample seem to have either fared equally well or equally badly in the aspects reviewed. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
There are only a few variations as detailed in the text, but they are not sufficiently major to warrant any special manner of performance ranking of the countries.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The major conclusion common to all the universities in the subregion is that, because of the increasingly precarious financial situation they are in, they are facing a serious prospect of intellectual extinction. }{\v <#/>}{
\v\fs24\lang2057 As such, they are facing a grim future in which they may soon no longer serve as "centres of excellence" or as "think-tanks" for their own nations in charting and expediting the development process.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 While this calls for serious soul-
searching on the part of the governments, particularly with respect to the attitude they have frequently held towards the universities, there is still an important implication for concerted action on the part of both the -governments and  the universities
. It is the search for and experimentation with other practical alternatives.
\par <h> }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Any Options? </h>
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Do universities, in the current unfavourable economic situation besetting the Third World and particularly Africa, have any options to take for a lasting solvency? }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
Looking at what they have on their agenda for intellectual, research and general cultural development - in the normal fashion of other universities - and looking at the bare emptiness of their coffers in the midst of the many government
al priorities and interventions, one could not but discern certain options that the universities cannot avoid if they have to survive and remain bona fide university institutions}{\fs24\lang2057 .</X></I> }{\v\fs24\lang2057 
