\par }{\b\i\fs24\lang2057 <X_>}{\b\i\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> }{\v <#/>}{\b\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Abstract </h>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{\v <#/>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Instead of talking of teaching and learning as they actually are in formal education institutions, we invariably end up talking of them as they ought to be. }{\v <#/>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 
Yet, if we really want to make positive educational changes, we need to begin with understanding them as they actually are. }{\v <#/>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 This paper contends 
that view of teaching as learning facilitation and of learning as a self-initiated process of the learner are at best idealistic. }{\v <#/>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 
What obtains in the reality of the school is adaptive and strategic learning which should be better labelled as "studenting", involving a repertoire of learning styles which the student uses to adjust to different teachers. }{\v <#/>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 
It is shown that teaching both as a family of activity-types as put fo
rward by Green and as a set of purposive acts making up a three-phase process of planning, encounter and evaluation, calls the learning tune which learners have no option but to dance to for their own survival. }{\v <#/>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 
It is highlighted that the transformation of teaching into the ideal must begin by recognizing, in addition, that the teaching styles with which students seek to align their learning style are determined to a large extent 
by the way teachers themselves learn.
