\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <h> }{<#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 The Concept of Learning  </h>
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 In a sense, le
arning is a reactive/adaptive change that an organism undergoes - a change in the way it relates to or makes sense of its environment. <#/>This may be a result of purely casual experience that may be conscious or unconscious. <#/>It sounds a rather passiv
e view of learning that is anachronistic. <#/>But psychologists have dealt with broad 'osmosis-type', non-deliberate and reactive learning as instrumental learning.
\par <#/>While such non-deliberate learning certainly does happen in a schooling context, it has not featured prominently in educational discourse except in the context of "the hidden curriculum" <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 (Giroux 1985)}{\fs24\lang2057 </X>
. <#/>Otherwise educators have tended to focus on and highlight what may be called 'intentional learning'; the learning that happens as a result
 of deliberate concerted effort by the organism itself as a 'change-initiator'. <#/>This has sometimes been referred to as operant learning. <#/>This form of learning sounds much more palatable and fashionably modern today when teaching has come to be con
ceived as a facilitation service to the active learner.
\par <#/>Admittedly, the term 'to learn' is variously used. <#/>There are times when it is used to mean to be taught something as in the sentence 'What do you learn at school? <#/>'. <#/>It is also used to 
mean to study, practice, exercise, memorize, enquire, search into something as in 'I am learning English on my own' . <#/>The third sense of the term is to gain knowledge, information, skill, mastery, comprehension or understanding of something . <#/>This
 is the achievement sense of the term. <#/>Thus one can use it with the auxiliary 'have' as in 'I have learned driving' . <#/>One cannot say 'I am learning English' in this sense if not in the other two senses presented above.
\par <#/>From this analysis, one se
nse of 'to learn' refers to achievement and not to a process. <#/>The other two senses refer to a process conceptualized in two ways, namely, learning as a process of adaptation, accommodation or reactive change; and learning as a process of change-initia
t
ion from within. <#/>The question at this point is: How does learning in these senses relate to teaching as a relationship; as a family of activity-types spread out on a continuum expressing a social relationship, and as a set of purposeful acts adding up
 to a process aiming at the facilitation of learning of another as presented above.
\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <h> }{<#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Relationship between Teaching and Learning </h>
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 When one examines the relationship between teaching and learning as processes, both aim at the achievement sense
 of learning although in different ways. <#/>In its intentional sense as a change-initiation process motivated from within the organism, learning aims at the organism's own or self-defined learning attainment. <#/>But in the adaptive or reactive sense, th
e learning process aims at other-defined as opposed to self-defined learning attainment.
\par <#/>On the other hand, if one takes teaching in global terms, it too aims at learning attainment. <#/>But, unlike in the case of the learning process, teaching aims at 
the learning of the student and not of the teacher himself or herself, or at least not exclusively. <#/>When we talk of the relationship of teaching to learning, we must bear in mind the two senses of learning just presented. <#/>Where learning is a proce
s
s of self-initiation, the teacher does not necessarily come in. <#/>If and when he/she does come in, it is merely as a resource person at the call of the learner; he or she does not come in to define for the learner the learning attainment, and the learne
r
 is at liberty to accept or reject the teacher's assistance. <#/>From the learner's viewpoint, the teaching is indeed a 'learning facilitation service' and no more, and learning is 'free learning'. <#/>However, in institutional formal education settings, 
t
he teacher is expected by the society not merely to facilitate learning, as it is fashionable to describe his role today, but to set learning expectations for the learners, while the learners are not expected to set their own agenda but to accommodate the
mselves to the expected learning attainments.
\par <#/>It is arguable that the view of teaching as a free facilitation service to the free active learning process of the learner is at best idealistic. <#/>In fact, it is an abstraction in the conventional formal 
educational settings. <#/>In the world of actuality, it is the teacher who calls the learning tune to which the learners must dance if they are to survive as students or pupils. <#/>While indeed teachers may try to adapt themselves to the learners, it is 
t
he latter who must adjust to the teacher. <#/>After all, the teacher deals with a variety of learners and it is not easy for him or her to adjust to each and every learner and so follow Cornett's advice: "the more the teacher knows about the child's learn
i
ng style, the more likely it is that the mediation will be effective", (1983:10). <#/>The reverse is closer to the truth, and students and pupils know this realism very well. <#/>This is in line with the power that society has conferred on teachers for se
tting learning agenda for learners. <X_>}{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
What learners engage in is therefore not essentially free and active learning but rather adaptive and strategic learning for their survival as students or pupils, given the existing power relations}{\fs24\lang2057 . }{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>It is therefor
e important to bear in mind the distinction between the ideal where learning is free and active and occurs on the learner's own terms and the real school world where learning is strategic, adaptive or reactive to teaching.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 It would seem that to teachin
g as a relation socially defined, it is adaptive-strategic learning which really corresponds while the active-intentional learning would correspond to teaching occurring outside or disregarding the socially defined relationship.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 If we look at teaching as a family of activity-types spread out on a continuum of Green, or even as a set of purposeful acts adding up to a three-stage process, there is no corresponding analysis of the concept of learning. }{
\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 This is understandable because in the world of schooling, learning has invariably been strategic and adaptive to teaching. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
It is therefore almost impossible to analyse free-intention learning within formal educational institutions. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Here, we are used to learning circumscribed by teaching as primaril
y a relationship which then is actualized in activity-types and purposeful acts. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
Studies which have been done on students' learning style reveal that for them, the learning process is indeed "the process of having students gradually become more adept at adjusting learning style to teaching style and the task..." (Cornett 1983:39). }{
\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 A similar conclusion was reached in a large-scale longitudinal research by Entwistle and Ramsden (1983) on understanding student learning.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 To avoid confusion we should rename students' school learning which is thus adaptive and strategic as "studenting" (or "pupiling"). }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
This is appropriate because, unlike learning, it implies also a socially defined relationship to teaching. In addition, analogous to teaching, it can be seen as a family of learning styles which a student engages in to actualize a known relation. }{\v 
<#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Such styles (or behavioural patterns) can be put on a continuum at the <AmE/>center of which will be those most strategic, and at the extremes, those least strategic for his/her survival as a student. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
The question to ask at this point is: what will be most strategic?
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Well, consistent with the framework developed above, this will depend on the teacher who calls the tune. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 In other words, the teac
hing style will influence the 'studenting' activity or learning style. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
Accordingly, Cornett (1983:14) maintains that we tend to teach not according to the way students learn, much as we would like it that way, rather "we tend to teach the way we learn, unless there is a conscious reason to do otherwise". }{\v <#/>}{
\v\fs24\lang2057 Thus, if as teachers we learn uncritically, for example, we will tend to preach or indoctrinate our students and expect them to be dogmatic believers and to be docile to us. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Students will accord
ingly adapt and make rote memorization a central activity in response. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 If we are left-brain dominant teachers, we may not like right-hemisphere learners and thus force them to adapt to us (Grady & Luecke 1978:13-20). }{\v <#/>}
{\v\fs24\lang2057 The students will have to quickly learn to style-flex from one teacher to another or decide to fail at the hands of some of them. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
That is the 'studenting' game leading to the readily learned lesson quoted at the beginning of this paper: "you don't write what you think, you write what the tutor wants you to think".
