\par <X_>}{\b\i\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> }{\v <#/>}{\b\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Abstract </h>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{\v <#/>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 This article uses a weak version hypothesis of contrastive analysis to determine the sources of errors in second language learning. }{\v <#/>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Previous
 studies on the subject have been made using the data of languages other than Bantu- to which Swahili belongs. }{\v <#/>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 The purpose of this study is to analyse performance data from English speakers learning Swahili.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Using the data of students' free compositions, the study suggests that in learning a}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 second language various strategies are adopted making it, difficult to trace errors from one source.
