\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <h> }{<#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Observations </h>}{\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 The differences of errors made in agreement as well as in word order between Group 1 and Group 2 provide interesting observations.
\par <#/>Errors which are most common for the intermediate and advanced subjects tend to indicate that increased proficiency in Swahili does not, in a strict sense, qualitatively affect the 'kinds' of 
errors which a learner makes. <#/>While the advanced subjects made fewer errors in word order and many in agreement, their most frequent errors were usually the errors which the intermediate subjects made most frequently. <#/>This case is similar for most
 of us who are non-native speakers of English; we are still making a lot of errors in the use of articles regardless of our proficiency in English.
\par <#/>Tied to the argument above is the role of the individual. <#/>It is possible to hypothesize that individu
als differ slightly in their strategies of language learning, specifically, in the case of agreement in Swahili. <#/>This was revealed in the data by the fact that the individuals' errors were not qualitatively uniform. <#/>This generalization has to be t
empered by the recognition that the subjects' background differs. <#/>Had we enough time and subjects, we could have controlled the subjects in such a way that they would all have been of the same background.
\par <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>Finally, the composition task with which the data was obtained proved to be an effective and objective procedure. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
Students had time to think about the compositions before handing them over to the author, unaware that their errors were to be analyzed for a paper of this kind.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 On the other hand, the results of the data and the conclusions made here are hampered by the fact that we only dealt with one task: free compositions. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
Had different tasks been performed, it is possible that our results and conclusions would have been different, as were the conclusions of Lo Coco (1976). }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
In comparing the performance of the second language learners on three different tasks, she found significant differ
ences across tasks, in the percentage of errors <-/occuring> in several <-/grammarical> categories, and also in the degree to which processes such as transfer and over generalization <-/occured>.
\par }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> }{\v <#/>}{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 Conclusion </h>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 What we have offered here is evidence of one task. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 But generally, the data has provided a first step in the investigation of this topic, and through which some interesting observations can be made.

\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The results lend support to the hypothesis that many of the errors could not be explained in terms of Ll transfer only, but rather should also be seen as coming from sources other than Ll.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The data suggest that the errors of individuals in both Group 1 and Group 2 quantitatively differ, confirming again the idea that individual learners adopt different strategies in learning a language. }{\v <#/>}{
\v\fs24\lang2057 Furthermore, some errors might be due to interference between various functions of the aspect of the language, itself.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The data also suggest that another possible source of errors might be "minor" interference factors such as interference from foreign languages that are learned before the target language.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 In summary, this study suggests that in learning a second language, various strategies are adopted. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Hence errors arising out of these strategies are difficult to trace to only one source. }{\v <#/>}{
\v\fs24\lang2057 These findings are in support of Jan's (1974) hypothesis that errors are traceable to both Ll and other than Ll sources. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 However, it is difficult to accurately attribute the source of a give "error". }{\v <#/>}
{\v\fs24\lang2057 For example, while Duskova attributes an error in the use of articles to interference, Dulay and Burt (1972) classify the same error as intralingual. }{\fs24\lang2057 </X></I>
